Hello, I am getting the following error while attempting to build this release with tensorrt on an Jetson AGX ORIGIN dev kit with Jetpack 5.0.1:  

`/home/ubuntu/repos/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/contrib_ops/cuda/quantization/qordered_ops/qordered_common.cuh(77): error: invalid narrowing conversion from "char" to "signed char"'
(several occurrences in the same phase)
`10 errors detected in the compilation of "/home/ubuntu/repos/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/contrib_ops/cuda/quantization/qordered_ops/qordered_attention_impl.cu".`

I use the following command to build:  
`./build.sh --config Release --update --build --parallel --build_shared_lib --use_tensorrt --use_tensorrt_builtin_parser --cuda_home /usr/local/cuda-11.4 --cudnn_home /usr/lib/aarch64-linux-gnu --tensorrt_home /usr/lib/aarch64-linux-gnu`

The same problem arises when building with `--config Debug` or `--config MinSizeRel`, or when leaving out `--use_tensorrt`.

Any clues how to circumvent this?

signed-off from PyTorch ONNX

When testing the Java GPU artifact in jshell on Linux x86_64 it's taking a *long* time on the `createSession` call. Not sure if it's CUDA compiling things or something else.

After trying a different machine it looks like something in createSession is waiting on a lock, as the thread is runnable but not actually running, and gdb says it's somewhere in pthread. Only occurs with the GPU jar, and I've only got Linux x86_64 GPU machines to test on, so I don't know what the behaviour is in Windows.

The threadpool is being constructed with some threads already started and waiting for dispatch.  Then something goes wrong, and it starts destructing and joining threads that already created, but there nothing to signal them to exit, since this was not accounted for.
While we do not know the root cause, we should have avoided the hang.

I will take a stub on it. An exercise in exception safety.

It would be nice to know what causes the destruction of the partially constructed TP. So if you could step with a debugger to see what is failing in the first place, that would be great, so we can address two things at once.

Otherwise, I will change the way things are constructed and we can retry, perhaps we could see some meaningful error message from the C++ exception, assuming they are propagated to Java layer.

Meaning C++ exceptions -> catch -> OrtStatus via C API -> Error on a Java JNI -> Java exception.

Thread creation can fail and throw exceptions in multiple places within `Env::CreateThread` and it is not being handled properly, so we hang.
